descript.abstract: Shapefile of of current NCAA Division 1 football stadiums, as of the 2006 football season. Methods note and sources: In some cases, the Sports Illustrated and NCAA websites (http://sportsilustrated.cnn.com/football/ncaa/teams and http://www.ncaafootball.com) were used to determine conference membership. Individual school websites (the .edu websites) were used to determine stadium shape, seating capacity, and, through use of the campus map, the location on campus. Stadium shape and capacity were crosschecked at the website http://www.collegegridirons.com . Physical locations of the stadiums was confirmed through comparison of the campus map with NAVTEQ road data in many cases; high resolution airborne imagery of major urban areas, and DOQQs of locations outside major urban areas were also used in some but not all cases to precisely locate the stadiums.
descript.purpose: NGA PMH has developed this shapefile as part of providing data for the Homeland Security Infrastructure Program (HSIP). This shapefile fullfiles part of the High Value/Symbolic layer, public venue sublayer.

Feature geometry.

Assets have been categorized by NGA Domestic Preparedness Branch analysts and assigned to a primary asset sector, using the HSIP Tiger Team Report, ver. 1.1, of September 2002 as a guideline for categorization.

Assets have been categorized by NGA Domestic Preparedness Branch analysts and assigned to an asset subsector, as defined in the HSIP Tiger Team Report, and as modified/expanded by domestic Preparedness Branch analysts to accommodate the given assets.

Assets have been categorized by NGA Domestic Preparedness Branch analysts and assigned to a Primary Type, as further categorization under a given subsector defined in the HSIP Tiger Team Report, and as modified/expanded by Domestic Preparedness Branch analysts to accommodate the given assets.
The security classification for an asset record. At this time, all assets in this shapefile are Unclassified.
The date, in YYYYMMDD format, when a record was created for the NCAA_Division_1_football_stadiums.

The date, in YYYYMMDD format, when a record was modified in any one of its fields. For mass record changes that involve the addition of an additional field, a note will be made at the end of this document and in the README document.
The college or university that the stadium is affiliated with. This could be on campus or off campus and either owned or not owned by the the school.
The primary accepted name of a site.
The secondary name of a site, if available, representing a higher-order relationship to the primary name in NAME1.
NAME3: The tertiary name of a site, if available, representing a higher-order relationship to the primary and secondary names in NAME1 and NAME2.

The street address at which a site is physically located, or a street corner at which a site is located, or non-specific location given in miles and a compass direction at which a site is physically located.
The second line for a street address, used to indicate a specific building, or a suite number, a room number, or a floor.
The Post Office box for a site, if known.
The 5- or 9-digit Zip Code for a site, if known and if different than the Zip Code for the physical address of the site.
The city or town in which the site is located.
The two letter postal identifier for the state, commonwealth, or territory in which the site is located.
The Zip Code for the site. Principally, this Zip Code is for where the site is physically located, although there exist some exceptions.
The Zip+4 for the site, if known, provided, or researched. COUNTY: The county, parish, or independent city name in which a site is located.
The county, parish, or independent city name in which a site is located.

The name of the Homeland Security Infrastructure Program (HSIP) area of interest (133 Cities Urban Area) within an asset is located. If the asset is not located within an HSIP_AOI, the value for the field is "None".)
The FBI Field Office that has responsibility for the area in which a stadium is located. Field Offices, and their areas of responsibility, can be located at the FBI web site http://www.fbi.gov .
The Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) region in which a site is located.
The Joint Regional Information Exchange System (JRIES) region in which a site is located.
The latitude, in decimal degrees, of a site, to 5 decimal places. Negative numbers in this field are for those locations in the Southern Hemisphere.
The longitude, in decimal degrees, of a site, to 5 decimal places. Negative numbers in this field are for those locations in the Western Hemisphere.

This rating (High, Medium, or LOW) by Domestic Preparedness analysts is an estimate of the reliability of the geocoordinates. These ratings are non-quantitative, but rather respectively represent whether the analyst believes the geocoordinates to be within a city block of the site's rooftop, to be within a kilometer of the site's rooftop, or to be beyond a kilometer of the actual physical site. In the case of assets that have been geocoded by either NIMA/NGA or TGS, a medium reliability is assigned, owing to how a geocoding service works. Geocoded coordinates will tend to be more accurate in urban areas with dense street grids versus rural areas with sparse street patterns. In some cases, additional comments about a site's location are included in the COMMENTS field.

The primary source used to determine a site's geocoordinates, although several sources may have been used to cross-check a location or street address. These other sources include maps, Web search sites, address geocoding functions, and customer-provided addresses and coordinates. --NIMA or NGA = Coordinates researched and verified by NIMA (prior to 11/24/2003) and NGA (after 11/24/2003).

This field is used for comments about the asset, in terms of name changes, ownership, pending sales, status/decommissioning, location, or certain details about activities at that asset. CAPACITY: The seating capacity of the stadium for football.
The seating capacity of the stadium for football.

The conference in which the college/university is a member for Division I football. --ACC: Atlantic Coast Conference --Big 12: Big 12 Conference --Big East: Big East Conference --Big Ten: Big Ten Conference --C-USA: Conference - USA --Independents: Independent (No conference afflitiation at this time.) --MAC: Mid American Conference --Mountain West: Mountain West Conference --Pac-10: Pacific 10 Conference --SEC: South Eastern Conference --Sun Belt: Sun Belt Conference --WAC: Western Athletic Conference
Describes the basic layout of the stands or stadium seating. --Horse Shoe: The stands are in a basic horse shape with one end open or with a building present or with a small number of stands. --
